ee   McShane  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>shine</i> ‘fair, handsome’ (Old English <i>scīene</i>). Compare   Sheen   2,   Shown   2, and   Shinn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Shinn","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): nickname from Middle English <i>shin(ne)</i> ‘fair, handsome’, a variant of   Shine   3 and   Sheen   2."]},{"name":"Shyne","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Shine  ."]},{"name":"McShane","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Conal, Declan, John Patrick, Kieran, Liam, Seamus.","Irish (northern): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Seáin</b> ‘son of <i>Seán</i>’, Irish form of   John  . The McShane family in Tyrone are a branch of the O'Neills."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Setting off’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":4,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":13,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":58,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de la Spine IV was born about 1324, in Coughton, Warwickshire, England, his father, William de la Spine, was 56 and his mother, Margery de Durvassal, was 45. He married Alice de Bruley in 1346, in Warwickshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1415, in his hometown, at the age of 92."},"et":{"about 1324–1415":"umbes 1324–1415","1306–Female":"1306–Surnud","1318–1318":"1318–1318","1324–1415":"1324–1415","1324–Female":"1324–Surnud","–1318":"–1318","1324–1425":"1324–1425","1360–1427":"1360–1427","1363–Male":"1363–Surnud","1270–1327":"1270–1327","1280–1375":"1280–1375","before 1299":"enne 1299","1363":"1363","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1327":"1327","1338":"1338","1415":"1415","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1346":"1346","1324":"1324","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","about 1324":"umbes 1324","about 1363":"umbes 1363","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","1427":"1427","1306":"1306","Coughton, Warwickshire, England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1324–1415":"noin 1324–1415","1306–Female":"1306–Kuollut","1318–1318":"1318–1318","1324–1415":"1324–1415","1324–Female":"1324–Kuollut","–1318":"–1318","1324–1425":"1324–1425","1360–1427":"1360–1427","1363–Male":"1363–Kuollut","1270–1327":"1270–1327","1280–1375":"1280–1375","before 1299":"ennen vuotta 1299","1363":"1363","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1327":"1327","1338":"1338","1415":"1415","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1346":"1346","1324":"1324","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","about 1324":"noin 1324","about 1363":"noin 1363","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","1427":"1427","1306":"1306","Co